    <h3>18.1 Exception :-</h3>

    <p>Exception is an abnormal condition that occurs during the execution of a program & due to which normal flow of the program's insrtuction may distrupt.</p>


    <b style="color:green;">Example :-</b>
    <code><pre>
class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Hello");
        System.out.println(5/0);
        System.out.println("Hello Again");
    }
}<br>
<strong style="color:black;">Output:- </strong>
        <samp>Hello</samp>
        <samp style="color:red;">Error :- Exception in main thread java.lang.ArithmeticException : / by zero</samp>
</pre></code>


    <hr>
</div>


<div>

    <h3>18.2 Exception Handling :-</h3>

    <p>It is a mechanism to handle the exception.</p>
    <p>Exception Handling is to maintain the normal flow of the application and to prevent abnormal termination of program.</p>
    <p>Some common exception</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Arithmetic Exception :- <code>int a = 5/0;</code></li>
        <li>Null Pointer Exception :- <code>String str = null;<br>System.out.println(s.length());</code></li>
    </ul>
    <b style="color:green;">Example :-</b>
    <code><pre>
class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int x = 10;
        int y = 20;
        if(x > y){
            System.out.println("x is greater than y");
        }else{
            System.out.println("x is less than y");
        }
    }
}<br>
<strong style="color:black;">Output:- </strong><samp>x is less than y</samp>
</pre></code>

    <hr>
</div>

<div>

    <h3>3.3 switch :-</h3>

    <p>switch statement are used to select one of many code blocks to be executed.</p>

    <b style="color:green;">Example :-</b>
    <code><pre>
class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int day = 3;
        switch (day) {
          case 1:
            System.out.println("Monday");
            break;
          case 2:
            System.out.println("Tuesday");
            break;
          case 3:
            System.out.println("Wednesday");
            break;
          case 4:
            System.out.println("Thursday");
            break;
          case 5:
            System.out.println("Friday");
            break;
          case 6:
            System.out.println("Saturday");
            break;
          case 7:
            System.out.println("Sunday");
            break;
        }
    }
}<br>
<strong style="color:black;">Output:- </strong><samp>Wednesday</samp>
</pre></code>

    <hr>
</div>

<div>

    <h3>3.4 for  :-</h3>

    <p>When we know exactly how many times you want to loop through a block of code, then we use the for loop.</p>

    <b style="color:green;">Example :-</b>
    <code><pre>
class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        for(int i = 0 ; i < 5 ; i++){
            System.out.print(i + " ");
        }
    }
}<br>
<strong style="color:black;">Output:- </strong><samp>0 1 2 3 4</samp>
</pre></code>

    <hr>
</div>


